{
  "success": true,
  "data": {
    "query": "ERCOT interconnection fee schedule milestone payment generation resource",
    "num_results": 5,
    "filters_applied": {
      "market": "ERCOT",
      "data_type": null,
      "year_start": null,
      "year_end": null,
      "range_type": null
    },
    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "c2995e81-75a7-4720-be2c-3b3782fec3d4",
        "score": 0.6939329,
        "text": "The document is an ERCOT fee schedule effective October 1, 2024. It outlines various fees related to ERCOT services, which are non-refundable unless specified by ERCOT Protocols.\n\n1. **Private Wide Area Network (WAN) Fees**:\n   - Based on actual costs for procuring, using, maintaining, and connecting to third-party networks for ERCOT WAN communications.\n   - Initial installation or reconfiguration costs capped at $7,000.\n   - Monthly network management fee capped at $450.\n\n2. **ERCOT Load Resource Registration and Generator Interconnection or Modification Fees**:\n   - $500 for registering a new Load Resource.\n   - Additional $500 if increasing MW size by more than 20% or changing registration type.\n   - Generator registration fees:\n     - $2,300 for Settlement Only Distribution Generators (SODGs).\n     - $8,000 for generators under 10 MW.\n     - $14,000 for generators 10 MW or greater.\n   - $8,000 for changing an existing SODG to a Distribution Generation Resource (DGR).\n\nThe document provides specific fee amounts and conditions for various registration and modification scenarios.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Fee_Schedule/page_2.jpg",
          "page_num": 2,
          "title": "ERCOT Fee Schedule",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "358386a7-6785-401f-bf79-ddf1ef8de19c",
        "score": 0.6687057,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures related to the Electric Reliability Council of Texas (ERCOT) regarding user fees and transmission billing determinants.\n\n1. **User Fees:**\n   - ERCOT is required to post user fees approved by the ERCOT Board on its website within two business days of any changes.\n   - Market Participants or other entities must pay these approved user fees.\n\n2. **Transmission Billing Determinant Calculation:**\n   - ERCOT provides Market Participants with necessary parameters and formulas to calculate billing charges for using Transmission or Distribution Facilities.\n   - ERCOT is not responsible for billing, collection, or disbursal of payments for transmission access service.\n\n3. **Billing Determinant Data Elements:**\n   - ERCOT calculates and provides data elements annually for Transmission Service Providers (TSPs) and Distribution Service Providers (DSPs) to use as billing determinants.\n   - Data must be provided by December 1 each year and comply with specific regulatory requirements.\n   - Key data elements include:\n     - The 4-Coincident Peak (4-CP) for each DSP and External Load Serving Entity (ELSE).\n     - The ERCOT average 4-CP.\n     - The average 4-CP for each DSP and ELSE coincident to the ERCOT average 4-CP.\n   - The ERCOT average 4-CP is the average of the coincidental MW peaks during June, July, August, and September.\n   - Coincidental MW peak is defined as the highest monthly Settlement Interval 15-minute MW peak for the entire ERCOT Transmission Grid, calculated using a specific formula involving net energy production and transfers.\n\nThe document also references updates to be made in accordance with NPRR995 and NPRR1188.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_9:_Settlement_and_Billing/page_52.jpg",
          "page_num": 52,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 9: Settlement and Billing",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "604622c0-b438-49d8-8d30-53eab9eec2f8",
        "score": 0.6662816,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures related to settlement and billing by ERCOT. Key points include:\n\n1. **Cost Evaluation and Reporting (Section 3):** \n   - Within 60 days of approving a profile segment, ERCOT evaluates submitted costs, disallowing those not meeting criteria. The remaining costs form the total reimbursable cost.\n   - ERCOT posts a report on its website summarizing allowed expenses.\n   - Market Participants can dispute ERCOT's determination within 45 days of the report posting.\n\n2. **Fee Calculation (Section 4):**\n   - If the requestor is a REP (Retail Electric Provider), the fee is calculated as FEE = $C / n.\n   - If not a REP, the fee is FEE = $C / (n + 1).\n   - Variables: \n     - $C = Total reimbursable cost\n     - n = Number of REPs subscribing to the profile segment\n\n3. **Fee Payment (Section 5):**\n   - Each subscribing REP must pay the fee to the requestor and previous REPs.\n   - As more REPs subscribe, the fee is recalculated and shared among all.\n\n4. **Assignment of ESI IDs (Section 6):**\n   - Four years after the profile segment is available, REPs can request assignment of Electric Service Identifiers without a development cost recovery fee.\n\n5. **Partial Payments by Invoice Recipients (Section 9.19):**\n   - ERCOT will attempt to collect payments from short-paying Invoice Recipients.\n   - ERCOT may draw on any pledged Financial Security if payments are not made in full.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_9:_Settlement_and_Billing/page_56.jpg",
          "page_num": 56,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 9: Settlement and Billing",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "1b6b9f97-40eb-4904-be64-6db1703fc6d2",
        "score": 0.64959526,
        "text": "The document page is from Section 9: Settlement and Billing of the ERCOT Nodal Protocols, dated February 1, 2025. It lists various sections related to payments and charges within the energy market. These include:\n\n- MRA (Market Resource Adequacy) payments and charges for capital expenditures, deployment events, variable payments, unexcused misconduct, and service charges.\n- Voltage support service payments and charges.\n- Black start services, including hourly standby fee and capacity charges.\n- Payments for emergency operations and real-time revenue neutrality allocation.\n- Emergency response service capacity payments and charges.\n- Firm fuel supply service payments, including hourly standby fee and capacity charges.\n- Real-time settlement for updated day-ahead market ancillary service obligations.\n- Regulation up and down service payments and charges.\n- Responsive reserve payments and charges.\n- Non-spinning reserve service payments and charges.\n- ERCOT contingency reserve service payments and charges.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_9:_Settlement_and_Billing/page_17.jpg",
          "page_num": 17,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 9: Settlement and Billing",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "e39a8580-984f-47c1-80aa-4509eba82827",
        "score": 0.6491951,
        "text": "The document page is from Section 9: Settlement and Billing of the ERCOT Nodal Protocols, dated February 1, 2025. It outlines various sections related to real-time payments, charges, and deviations in the energy market. Key points include:\n\n- Real-time payments and charges for block load transfer points, high dispatch limits, and energy from specific generators and storage systems.\n- Congestion payments and charges for self-schedules.\n- Set point deviation charges for over and under generation, as well as for controllable load resources and energy storage resources.\n- RMR (Reliability Must-Run) payments, adjustments, charges for unexcused misconduct, and service charges.\n- Methods for reconciling RMR costs and expenses.\n- MRA (Market Resource Adequacy) standby payments.\n\nEach section specifies different aspects of settlement and billing related to energy generation, storage, and consumption.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_9:_Settlement_and_Billing/page_16.jpg",
          "page_num": 16,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 9: Settlement and Billing",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

